Title: Fraggle Rock: Complete Second Season

reviewText: Growing up in Toronto Canada, I remember watching Fraggle Rock on CBC when I was just a kid.  Some kids shows you enjoy as a kid but when you grow up you look back and ask "why did I watch this?" but this isn't the case.  Fraggle Rock, like many Jim Henson Productions is both entertaining for young children but has enough humour and intelligence to appeal to an adult audience.  It also delivers great morals and lessons which unlike some other children's shows don't come across as (what TV tropes calls:  Anvilicious, morals and lessons so unsubtle you might as well engrave the message into an anvil and drop it on the viewer's head).The special features are really good too.  I like the feature talking about the different "Doc and Sprocket" segments filmed for different countries.  It's an interesting look at how an international co-production works, especially in today's age where everyone seems to want the "original version" and is quick to scream, "It's been re-edited/dubbed!  They've ruined it!".  I also loved the "All around the world" music video for Travelling Matt, so much I put it on my itunes.
Title: Fraggle Rock: Complete Second Season

reviewText: Fraggle Rock's second season is even better than the first.  Many shows can say this.  The spend the first year getting the characters nailed down and figuring things out.  In this case-- it isn't just that.  Saving set the ground rules for the series, Jerry Juhl and the other writers then set out to break a few of them.  The Gorgs no longer appear in almost every episode.  They're still around but they are a lot more episodes with entirely internal conflicts- either amongst where character or the Fraggle Community.  Second- there are episodes without Gobo or Uncle Matt.  Thirdly- at least from my perspective- there are a lot more episodes that focus on Boober.

reviewText: Watching this series of classic Fraggle Rock episodes made me realize the genius behind the Henson machine.  Who else can talk to kids about complex social issues in such a clear cut manner without dumbing things down?  No one.  The Muppet Master is truly missed in this cynical day and age.Excellent viewing for the whole family.  Jim Henson's Muppets at their finest.
summary: Thet Don't Make 'Em Like This Anymore
Title: Fraggle Rock: Complete Second Season

reviewText: The print quality of the DVD's is fantastic. Keep in mind that the series was originally shot with video tape, so it's never going to be HD quality. But the print looks as good as it ever has.You get what you'd expect from any TV season on DVD. All the episodes and a few extras. The focus is on the episodes though.You won't be unhappy with the quality. And the box is a nice sturdy contruction so it'll hold up to kids playing with it.
